onal realm: Eupen-Malmedy in the interbellum period (1920–1940) -- tChapter 10. Multilingual education and the politics of language in Luxembourg -- tChapter 11. In contact and/or in conflict? Ethno-cultural markers, language and schooling in post-war Brussels -- tEpilogue -- tChapter 12. Conceptualising “language borders”, “language contact” and “language conflict” -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume revisits the issue of language contact and conflict in the Low Countries across space and time. The contributions deal with important sites of Germanic-Romance contact along the different language borders, covering languages such as French, Dutch, German, and Luxembourgish. This first monograph in English on the topic broadens our understanding of current-day issues by integrating a historical perspective, showing how language contact and conflict operated from the Middle Ages and the Early Modern Period, the 18th and 19th centuries, and into the 20th and 21st centuries.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aGermanic languagesxSocial aspects. 0aHistorical linguisticszEurope. 0aLanguages in contactzEurope. 0aRomance languagesxSocial aspects. 0aSociolinguisticszEurope. 4aSoziolinguistik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aGermanic Languages.  aHistorical Sociolinguistics.  aLanguage Contact.  aRomance Languages.  aSociolinguistics.1 aBoemer, Magali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarquennes, Jeroen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrijhoff, Willem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeijde, M. C. A. Kessels-van der, econtributor.4ctb4https://